Streptomyces albolongus YIM 101047 was isolated from an Elephas maximus faeces sample in Yunnan Province in China. It could produce nine baﬁlomycins, including three new compounds, 19-methox- ybaﬁlomycin C1 amide (compound 1; 240 μg/L), 21-deoxybaﬁlomycin A1 (compound 2; 43 μg/L), and 21-deoxybaﬁlomycin A2 (compound 3; 64 μg/L) (Fig. S1). Baﬁlomycin is best known as a vacuolar-type ATPase inhibitor (Bowman et al., 1988; Werner et al., 1984). Several analogs of baﬁlomycin have antibacterial, antifungal, antitumor, antiparasitic, and/or immunosuppressant activities (Del Poeta et al., 2000; Goetz et al., 1985; Vanek et al., 1991; Wilton et al., 1985). Compound 1 was cytotoxic to four human cancer cell lines, with IC50 values ranging from 1.36 to 5.02 μM; compound 2 showed strong antifungal activity against Candida parapsilosis, with MIC value of 3.13 μg/mL (Fig. S1) (Ding et al., 2016). The baﬁlomycin biosynthetic gene clusters were previously cloned from Streptomyces lohii JCM 14114 (Zhang et al., 2013) and Streptomyces griseus DSM 2608 (Hwang et al., 2013). How- ever, the function of many genes involved in its biosynthetic pathway was still uncharacterized. In addition to plecomarolide baﬁlomycins, S. albolongus YIM 101047 could also produce seven odoriferous sesqui- terpenoids, including two new compounds, (1β,4β,4aβ,8aα)-4,8adi- (compound 4; 50 μg/L) methyloctahydronaphthalene-1,4a(2H)-diol

Jiang). journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/jbiotec Streptomyces albolongus YIM 101047 produces novel baﬁlomycins and odoriferous sesquiterpenoids with cyto- toxic and antimicrobial activities. Here, we report the complete genome sequence of S. albolongus YIM 101047, which consists of an 8,027,788 bp linear chromosome. Forty-six putative biosynthetic gene clusters of secondary metabolites were found. The sesquiterpenoid gene cluster was on the left arm (0.09–0.10 Mb), and the baﬁlo- mycin biosynthetic gene cluster was on the right arm (7.46–7.64 Mb) of the chromosome. Twenty-two putative gene clusters with high or moderate similarity to important antibiotic biosynthetic gene clusters were found, including the antitumor agents baﬁlomycin, epothilone and hedamycin; the antibacterial/antifungal agents clavulanic acid, collismycin A, frontalamides, kanamycin, streptomycin and streptothricin; the protein phos- phatase inhibitor RK-682; and the acute iron poisoning medication desferrioxamine B. The genome sequence reported here will enable us to study the biosynthetic mechanism of these important antibiotics and will fa- cilitate the discovery of novel secondary metabolites with potential applications to human health.

Compound 4 showed strong antifungal activity against Candida albicans and C. parapsilosis, with MIC value of 12.5 μg/mL and 3.13 μg/mL, respectively (Fig. S1) (Ding et al., 2016). A phylogenic tree based on 16S rRNA sequences, constructed by using MEGA (version 7.0) and neighbor-joining method, showed a distinct branch of S. albolongus YIM 101047 with other Streptomyces strains (Fig. 1). Obtaining the complete genome sequence of S. albo- longus YIM 101047 would lead to further understanding of the bio- synthetic mechanism of these important compounds, which would fa- cilitate future work to improve their productivity and to generate novel analogs through genetic engineering. The complete genome of S. albolongus YIM 101047 was obtained by using Illumina HiSeq 4000 sequencing platform and Pacbio RSII plat- form. After ﬁltering the raw data by Soapnuke (Li et al., 2009) and SMRT analysis 2.3.0 (Chin et al., 2013) software, approximately 1141 Mb Hiseq clean data and 755 Mb Pacbio subreads were generated. The Pacbio subreads was assembled with RS_HGAP_Assembly.3 in SMRT Analysis v2.3.0, four assembly methods were used, including HGAP3 correction and Celera assembly, HGAP3 correction and Falcon assembly, Falcon correction and Celera assembly and Facon correction Table 1 Genome features of S. albolongus YIM 101047.

and Falcon assembly. The assembly was polished using Quiver (Chin et al., 2013). Then, the assembled genome was further polished using Pilon with Hiseq clean data (Walker et al., 2014). The average depth of genome coverage was 236-fold. The complete genome of S. albolongus YIM 101047 was composed of a linear chromosome of 8,027,788 bp with a GC content of 71.98%. The protein coding sequences were predicted with Glimmer (v3.02) at NCBI (Delcher et al., 2007), and the gene functions were annotated using the NCBI Prokaryotic Genome Annotation Pipeline. The chromosome contained 6980 genes, including 6713 protein coding genes, 18 rRNA genes, 65 tRNA genes, 3 ncRNA genes, and 181 pseudo genes (Table 1 and Fig. 2). The identiﬁed genes were classiﬁed into 5919, 14,599, and 6700 categories based on clus- ters of orthologous genes of proteins (COG), gene ontology (GO), and Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) designation, re- spectively (Figs. S2, S3, and S4, note that genes might be classiﬁed into more than one category). Four genomes of Streptomyces strains, including Streptomyces sp. CFMR 7, Streptomyces globisporus C-1027, Streptomyces sp. Tue6075 and Streptomyces griseus subsp. griseus NBRC 13350, were chosen for com- parative genomics analysis with S. albolongus YIM 101047. All ﬁve strains contained putative baﬁlomycins and sesquiterpenoids gene clusters with high similarity. Structural variation analysis (Kurtz et al., 2004) at nucleic acid level and amino acid level revealed high levels of similarity between S. albolongus YIM 101047 and other four Streptomyces strains, and the variations in the location of genes might be caused by recombination and transposition (Fig. S5). To fur- ther show the functional diﬀerences and similarities among the ﬁve closely related strains, pan genes were assigned to construct a heatmap (Fig. S6). BLAST coverage ratios (BCR) values of genes were calculated to show the homology of compared genomes. According to core and pan gene analysis (Qin et al., 2010), 5535 genes were assigned to core genes, most of which were the genes necessary for growth; 9327 genes were assigned to pan genes. S. albolongus YIM 101047 and Streptomyces sp. CFMR 7 shared more dispensable genes than the other two strains. Phylogenetic trees (Nandi et al., 2010) based on core and pan gene analysis and gene family analysis were constructed to ﬁnd the evolu- tionary relationship of the four strains (Fig. S7). S. albolongus YIM 101047 was evolutionarily closest to Streptomyces sp. CFMR 7.

The biosynthetic gene clusters for putative secondary metabolites were identiﬁed using the antiSMASH 3.0 program (Weber et al., 2015) and veriﬁed by manual inspection. Forty-six putative biosynthetic gene clusters were found, including seven nonribosomal peptides, six poly- ketides, six terpenes, four polyketide-nonribosomal peptides, four sac- charides, four siderophores, two fatty acids, one blactam, one ectoine, one lantipeptide, one lassopeptide, one linaridin, and seven other me- tabolites (Table 2 and Fig. 3). Thirteen putative gene clusters showed high similarity (> 70% of genes show similarity) to reported iso- renieratene, geosmin, griseobactin, coelichelin, ectoine, desferriox- amine B, streptothricin, SRO15-2005, Amfs, collismycin A, baﬁlomycin, frontalamides, and melanin gene clusters. Nine putative gene clusters showed moderate similarity (30%–70% of genes show similarity) to reported streptomycin, RK-682, clavulanic acid, legonaridin, heda- mycin, macrotetrolide, kanamycin, hopene, and epothilone gene clus- ters. The existence of these putative gene clusters indicated that S. al- bolongus YIM 101047 has the potential to produce these important antibiotics or their analogs. Twenty putative gene clusters showed low similarity (< 30% of genes show similarity) to reported herboxidiene, friulimicin, steﬃmycin, nataxazole, A54145, SCO-2138, phospho- noglycans, marineosin, viomycin, skyllamycin, kanamycin, pactamycin,

Four putative gene clusters were not conserved relative to any known cluster. The existence of these cryptic secondary metabolite biosyn- thetic gene clusters implies that S. albolongus YIM 101047 could be a potential source for novel antibiotic discovery.

The baﬁlomycin biosynthetic gene cluster in S. albolongus YIM 101047 showed high similarity to that in Streptomyces griseus DSM 2608 and Streptomyces lohii JCM 14114. All the three baﬁlomycin gene clusters contained eighteen genes with high similarity (89%–98%) and identity (87%–97%) at the amino acid level (Table S1). These genes might be essential for baﬁlomycin biosynthesis, only four of them (bafZ, 5-aminolevulinic acid synthase; bafAIII, polyketide synthase; bafSV, polyketide synthase; bafAIV, FkbH-like protein) had been characterized in vivo/in vitro previously (Hwang et al., 2013; Zhang et al., 2013). Function studies of the rest of fourteen core genes are needed to further clarify the formation of baﬁlomycin and its shunt products. In addition to B7C62_33115 (AfsR family) and B7C62_33125 (LuxR family), ﬁve putative transcriptional (B7C62_33010, B7C62_33175, B7C62_33190, B7C62_33200 and B7C62_33215) around the core genes were found in S. albolongus YIM 101047 genome, these genes might regulate baﬁlomycin biosynthesis. Moreover, the roles of some genes located upstream and downstream of the core genes in S. albolongus YIM 101047 genome need to be conﬁrmed. The putative sesquiterpe- noid biosynthetic gene cluster in S. albolongus YIM 101047 showed high similarity to the putative geosmin gene cluster in Streptomyces fulvis- simus DSM 40593, Streptomyces sp. A 737-amino acid terpene synthase/cyclase (B7C62_00490) was found in S. albolongus YIM 101047, it showed moderate identity (68%) to the well char- acterized geosmin synthase (SCO6073) in S. coelicolor A3(2) (Jiang and Cane, 2008; Jiang et al., 2007). Two TetR family transcriptional reg- ulators and a putative ABC transporter permease were found near B7C62_00490, which might regulate the biosynthesis of the novel sesquiterpenoids discovered from S. albolongus YIM odoriferous 101047. In conclusion, S. albolongus YIM 101047 could produce novel compounds with cytotoxic and antimicrobial activities, obtaining and analyzing the complete genome sequence of this strain suggested it has a good potential for novel natural products discovery. In addition, the biosynthesis mechanism of the bioactive novel compounds isolated from this strain should be further understood to improve their pro- ductivity and to generate novel analogs through genetic engineering. Nucleotide sequence accession number The complete genome sequence of S. albolongus YIM 101047 was deposited at GenBank under accession number CP020563. This strain had been deposited at the Yunnan Institute of Microbiology under ac- cession number YIM 101047.
